problem:
Which of the following reactions is allowed? If forbidden, state the reason:
(a) \(\pi^- + \mathrm{p} \rightarrow \mathrm{K}^- + \Sigma^+\);
(b) \(\mathrm{d} + \mathrm{d} \rightarrow \mathrm{He}^4 + \pi^0\);
(c) \(\mathrm{K}^- + \mathrm{p} \rightarrow \mathrm{E}^- + \mathrm{K}^+\).

Consider a non-degenerate doped semiconductor where the carrier generation transitions from impurity ionization to intrinsic excitation with increasing temperature. Using phosphorus in silicon as an example (with a phosphorus ionization energy in silicon, \(E_{I}=0.045 \ \text{eV}\)), calculate the temperature at the onset of saturation ionization and the onset of intrinsic excitation when the phosphorus impurity concentration is \(10^{17} \ \text{cm}^{-3}\).

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{ccc}
\hline
Concentration \(/\left(\mathrm{cm}^{-3}\right)\) & \(T_{1} / \mathrm{K}\) & \(T_{2} / \mathrm{K}\) \\
\hline
\(1 \times 10^{17}\) & 281 & 761 \\
\(1 \times 10^{14}\) & 77 & 461 \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

Consider a non-degenerate doped semiconductor where the carrier generation transitions from impurity ionization to intrinsic excitation with increasing temperature. Using phosphorus in silicon as an example (with a phosphorus ionization energy in silicon, \(E_{I}=0.045 \ \text{eV}\)), calculate the temperature at the onset of saturation ionization and the onset of intrinsic excitation when the phosphorus impurity concentration is \(10^{14} \ \text{cm}^{-3}\).

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{ccc}
\hline
浓度 \(/\left(\mathrm{cm}^{-3}\right)\) & \(T_{1} / \mathrm{K}\) & \(T_{2} / \mathrm{K}\) \\
\hline
\(1 \times 10^{17}\) & 281 & 761 \\
\(1 \times 10^{14}\) & 77 & 461 \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

solution:
导带电子有效质量

\[
m_{\mathrm{n}}^{*}=\frac{h^{2}}{\frac{\mathrm{d}^{2} E_{C}}{\mathrm{~d} k^{2}}}
\]

由题意

\[
\begin{gathered}
\frac{\mathrm{d}^{2} E_{C}}{\mathrm{~d} k^{2}}=\frac{2 h^{2}}{3 m_{0}}+\frac{2 h^{2}}{m_{0}}=\frac{8 h^{2}}{3 m_{0}} \\
m_{\mathrm{n}}^{*}=\frac{3 m_{0}}{8}=\frac{3 \times 9.1 \times 10^{-31}}{8}=3.41 \times 10^{-31} \, \mathrm{kg} = 0.375 m_{0}
\end{gathered}
\]

